sharing with one million of their best friends

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:40.010
kind of thing.

00:10:40.010 --> 00:10:43.709
&gt;&gt;Ryan: Yeah, I think part of it's about the
premise that it's founded on. We were somewhat

00:10:43.709 --> 00:10:47.810
fortunate through product decisions and, and
just luck in terms of stumbling on a certain

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:51.890
model that that resonate, but people came
to the service having that expectation from

00:10:51.890 --> 00:10:56.529
day one. And you opt into that and that expectation
is shared throughout the network. When you

00:10:56.529 --> 00:11:00.450
start on a premise of private and small networks
and have to then shift the user base to an

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:02.910
area where you want them to share. I think
that's where a lot of the consternations starts

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:10.400
to happen because most users aren't in tune
enough in the same way we are in the valley

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:13.850
around like, what all that actually means,
what the implications five to ten years down

00:11:13.850 --> 00:11:15.570
the road are. So it's very hard to let them
understand the nuances over time. So, we've

00:11:15.570 --> 00:11:19.400
been fortunate that we started out with that
initial premise and that seems to be the one

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:22.940
that people are trending towards and we're
able to stay where we are and that just--

00:11:22.940 --> 00:11:24.620
&gt;&gt;Kara: You're adding more specific things,
