human nature. I mean, there's, you're trying

00:12:58.550 --> 00:13:02.029
to take it and make it this digital thing
that has knobs and selections. And there's

00:13:02.029 --> 00:13:05.800
different types of relationships and data
flows much more easily, which I think is also

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:11.649
harder when you're dealing with human relationships
it's a little easier to keep it contained.

00:13:11.649 --> 00:13:13.440
But where it's digital and it can flow throughout
the network and be syndicated out to millions

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:18.600
of people across the world instantly. It changes
the nature of how you have to think about

00:13:18.600 --> 00:13:19.600
it.

00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:20.600
&gt;&gt;Kara: But explaining it to people is that
hard? I mean, I think they're, they're aggressively,

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:21.600
purposefully being confusing in a lot of ways.

00:13:21.600 --> 00:13:27.810
&gt;&gt;Chris: So, actually, I would, I would respond
to that. Because it's been interesting to

00:13:27.810 --> 00:13:32.100
watch how Facebook has tried to explain some
of these things. Specifically, my girlfriend

00:13:32.100 --> 00:13:37.019
was using Facebook. And there was some time
many months ago they put up this "terms of

00:13:37.019 --> 00:13:40.480
service change" thing where they were inviting
people to go participate. To read whatever

00:13:40.480 --> 00:13:44.620
it was they were gonna change. And it was
there for two or three days at the top of

00:13:44.620 --> 00:13:48.779
the News Feed, I think this was before the
redesign. And I asked her several days after

00:13:48.779 --> 00:13:53.110
when she was like surprised that the terms
had changed. Like, "Didn't you see that thing

00:13:53.110 --> 00:13:54.360
sitting at the top of your News Feed, like
blocking your view?" And she's like, "Oh.

00:13:54.360 --> 00:14:00.690
I saw that but I just, I didn't engage with
it." So, we've had a similar experience with

00:14:00.690 --> 00:14:04.290
Buzz. Where we've also provided certain types
of disclosure about: " Look, you know, you

00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:10.050
can enable this if you really want to" but
I think people are oftentimes, they have an

00:14:10.050 --> 00:14:14.360
objective in mind when they arrive at something
and they're gonna blow through whatever else

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:15.360
gets in their way.

00:14:15.360 --> 00:14:16.829
&gt;&gt;Kara: Perhaps, I mean, unless you give them
a chance. One of the things we did on our,

00:14:16.829 --> 00:14:19.819
we, Walt was very particular about making
people aware of cookies and --

00:14:19.819 --> 00:14:20.819
&gt;&gt;Chris: Sure.

00:14:20.819 --> 00:14:24.550
&gt;&gt;Kara: our headline was "We're watching everything
you do right now. Do you want to do something

00:14:24.550 --> 00:14:29.610
about it?" We were very; we were very, getting
their attention. We're sneakily following

00:14:29.610 --> 00:14:30.870
you everywhere on the Web. They're always
to alert people.

00:14:30.870 --> 00:14:33.199
&gt;&gt;Chris: And I guess if you use it like that,
like, like there's someone looking over your

00:14:33.199 --> 00:14:36.730
shoulder right now, don't turn around kind
of thing. I mean, maybe that would work, but

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:40.430
I think when we try to do all these things
across all these different sites in a way

00:14:40.430 --> 00:14:41.720
that isn't too alarmist--

00:14:41.720 --> 00:14:42.720
&gt;&gt;Kara: Right.

00:14:42.720 --> 00:14:45.579
&gt;&gt;Chris: but still informs, I mean, you're
right, unless we're screaming at them.

00:14:45.579 --> 00:14:47.120
&gt;&gt;Kara: Why not be alarmist?

00:14:47.120 --> 00:14:48.120
&gt;&gt;Chris: I think that--

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:53.011
&gt;&gt;Kara: The weird guy from high school can
find you now. Something like that.

00:14:53.011 --> 00:14:58.130
&gt;&gt;Chris: I do want to AB test that. You guys
wanna try that?

00:14:58.130 --> 00:14:59.509
[panel laughter]

00:14:59.509 --> 00:15:11.709
&gt;&gt;Kara: So, Microsoft, one of you guys, how
do you look at the, cause you have a business

00:15:11.709 --> 00:15:17.490
part that is quite privacy oriented and then
you have struggled in a consumer space more.

00:15:17.490 --> 00:15:32.060
But how do you look at this idea where people
are doing this aggressive sharing?

00:15:32.060 --> 00:15:46.649
&gt;&gt;Angus: I think the key thing is that privacy
is in our DNA. I mean, like you said that

00:15:46.649 --> 00:15:53.300
there's the business side where we are quite
private. There's one privacy, like, central

00:15:53.300 --> 00:16:00.100
organization inside Microsoft or our Trustworthy
Computing. That's a part of every engineering

00:16:00.100 --> 00:16:06.769
process, whether you're working on like, shippable
software, like box product, or whether you're

00:16:06.769 --> 00:16:11.339
working on online services. So, I mean, when
it comes to Windows Live, specifically, I

00:16:11.339 --> 00:16:28.360
think a lot of what Chris said is, is important.
Like, do not surprise people. And the scary

00:16:28.360 --> 00:16:36.730
thing about that is if someone's surprised
then you've already done something wrong.

00:16:36.730 --> 00:16:45.990
Like, people need to be able to choose who
can see what of theirs and they need to be

00:16:45.990 --> 00:17:00.689
able to get granular or that we need to make
sure that the defaults are set to an appropriate

00:17:00.689 --> 00:17:20.590
level. So, it's just about expectation management.
And I mean, with, I think it's about 500 million

00:17:20.590 --> 00:17:28.590
people currently have Windows Live ID's, that's
a huge number of people that are, that we

00:17:28.590 --> 00:17:32.080
want to make sure we get privacy right for.

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:37.910
&gt;&gt;Kara: Mm-hmm. Do you think it's because
Microsoft's, I mean, of all, I mean, based

00:17:37.910 --> 00:17:43.030
on the promiscuous scale, Facebooks way down
here, Microsoft hasn't been as successful

00:17:43.030 --> 00:17:48.360
because their lack of promiscuity. I'm trying
to-- you know what I mean?

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:52.520
&gt;&gt;Angus: I mean, I'm not even gonna go there,
actually.

00:17:52.520 --> 00:17:54.600
&gt;&gt;Kara: You're not as easy!

00:17:54.600 --> 00:17:55.600
[panel laughter]

00:17:55.600 --> 00:17:56.600
&gt;&gt;Angus: Yeah.

00:17:56.600 --> 00:17:57.600
[pause]

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:00.390
&gt;&gt;Kara: But, why, why, you need to have to
do that?

00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:01.390
[laughter]

00:18:01.390 --> 00:18:06.670
Do you need to have to get there to be successful;
to be that, you know, give--

00:18:06.670 --> 00:18:17.060
&gt;&gt;Angus: I don't think so. I think you can
build a perfectly good business that satis--,

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:20.820
that satisfies tons of consumers and advertisers
by keeping everything legit.

00:18:20.820 --> 00:18:25.990
&gt;&gt;Kara: Right. I'll move to a vacuum cleaner
metaphor. They have a giant sucking vacuum

00:18:25.990 --> 00:18:34.620
cleaner; yours is less, set on a less level.
I mean, can you be successful when it's not

00:18:34.620 --> 00:18:45.260
like that? When it's not sucking every piece
of information ever about you in-, indiscriminately?

00:18:45.260 --> 00:18:52.100
&gt;&gt;Angus: I think you can absolutely be successful.
Yeah, definitely.

00:18:52.100 --> 00:18:53.100
[laughter]

00:18:53.100 --> 00:19:02.960
&gt;&gt;Kara: LinkedIn guy, dude, so you guys I
have to say I think do have the most, the

00:19:02.960 --> 00:19:11.880
easiest used tools. To-- and the people on
LinkedIn do want to share. They want to share

00:19:11.880 --> 00:19:17.770
information about themselves a lot for jobs,
a lot for job search, and stuff like that.

00:19:17.770 --> 00:19:25.740
So the intent is very clear. I find the tools
simple to use; it's very clear about how,

00:19:25.740 --> 00:19:32.200
what you're putting up, who's getting what
and it's actually quite protective about a

00:19:32.200 --> 00:19:33.200
lot of things.

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:48.110
&gt;&gt;Adam: Well, I think that's, that's actually
part of makes these problems so hard is that--

00:19:48.110 --> 00:19:49.570
&gt;&gt;audience1: Microphone.

00:19:49.570 --> 00:19:55.940
&gt;&gt;Adam: Sorry? I think that's part of makes
it such a hard problem across the, the social

00:19:55.940 --> 00:20:03.430
Web is that context really matters. This isn't
just a technical problem, it isn't just a

00:20:03.430 --> 00:20:15.010
cognitive problem understanding what we could
or couldn't do. The fact is no one ever writes

00:20:15.010 --> 00:20:30.010
down social contracts, right? Communities
form, then they evolve. We've been very fortunate,

00:20:30.010 --> 00:20:40.470
you know. LinkedIn's always taken privacy
very seriously because in business context

00:20:40.470 --> 00:20:45.510
there is some information that you really
do guard, right? If you're unhappy with your

00:20:45.510 --> 00:20:52.930
employer and you're looking around for a new
job, that's something very private. We take

00:20:52.930 --> 00:21:02.690
it very seriously that we always want people
on LinkedIn to feel like they put their best

00:21:02.690 --> 00:21:11.340
foot forward. We would never want to embarrass
someone. On the flip side, LinkedIn users

00:21:11.340 --> 00:21:18.740
have always been, ever since we launched the
feature, delighted to find out that the first

00:21:18.740 --> 00:21:23.580
time that someone Googles them, that their
LinkedIn profile comes up high because that

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:27.800
professional side of you, that professional
persona that we all spend decades kind of

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:34.010
working on through our careers; that's actually
the default one that a lot people are comfortable

00:21:34.010 --> 00:21:35.600
with a stranger seeing.

00:21:35.600 --> 00:21:36.600
&gt;&gt;Kara: Mm-hmm.

00:21:36.600 --> 00:21:42.820
&gt;&gt;Adam: And so, I think yeah, LinkedIn has
done well in this area, but I think that's

00:21:42.820 --> 00:21:47.160
partially because we're very focused on our
context and what users want from that context.

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:56.140
&gt;&gt;Kara: But you don't have a whole lot of
information on your thing. I mean, I love

00:21:56.140 --> 00:22:02.080
LinkedIn because if I, I'm able to reach all
the Yahoo executives I want to leak to me,

00:22:02.080 --> 00:22:03.080
for example, but--

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:04.080
[laughter]

00:22:04.080 --> 00:22:07.790
and Facebook works really well, too. Sorry.
Not you. So, not yet.

00:22:07.790 --> 00:22:08.790
[laughter]

00:22:08.790 --> 00:22:17.190
Do you need to add more stuff to that because
you imagine having, you don't have any pictures,

00:22:17.190 --> 00:22:23.390
it's somewhat, not, that's not the right word.
It's somewhat plain vanilla kind of stuff.

00:22:23.390 --> 00:22:25.400
&gt;&gt;Adam: Well, yeah, it's focused--

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:38.030
&gt;&gt;Kara: It's like a resume. It's looking at
someone's resume with a little bit more.

00:22:38.030 --> 00:22:55.650
&gt;&gt;Adam: Yeah, but, it's only a mix of information
that people share etc., but for the most part,

00:22:55.650 --> 00:23:08.610
yeah, your professional profile first and
foremost is that first value proposition that

00:23:08.610 --> 00:23:15.470
people get. That, "Hey, when someone looks
for me online, they're gonna see me this way.

00:23:15.470 --> 00:23:24.460
This is my role at LinkedIn and previously
I worked at these companies. I went to this

00:23:24.460 --> 00:23:30.330
school." We spend a good chunk of our lives
accumulating these experiences and skills

00:23:30.330 --> 00:23:38.520
and so I wouldn't say we don't have a lot
of information, I think it actually is not

00:23:38.520 --> 00:23:44.340
only a significant amount of information,
I think it's very important to people. It's

00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:53.880
just in this context. That's how people want
to present it.

00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:59.450
&gt;&gt;Kara: Can you imagine having more information
there? Like, more pictures, videos, things

00:23:59.450 --> 00:24:00.480
like that?

00:24:00.480 --> 00:24:08.060
&gt;&gt;Adam: To be honest, we're very, we react
what our users want. So I think that as more

00:24:08.060 --> 00:24:14.960
and more users want more rich content, we'll
probably provide more rich content. But really

00:24:14.960 --> 00:24:30.200
it responds to what do people feel like they
need to represent themselves professionally

00:24:30.200 --> 00:24:38.880
online. To date, that hasn't involved a lot
of that rich media.

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:39.910
&gt;&gt;Kara: Mm-hmm.

00:24:39.910 --> 00:24:46.630
&gt;&gt;Adam: People don't feel like they need to
represent themselves professionally with photo

00:24:46.630 --> 00:24:49.840
albums of their kids or that sort of thing.

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:50.840
&gt;&gt;Kara: Right, right.

00:24:50.840 --> 00:24:55.400
&gt;&gt;Adam: I don't think that that's likely.

00:24:55.400 --> 00:25:06.770
&gt;&gt;Kara: Right, that's what I think. Let's
move on to, from, before you get into privacy,

00:25:06.770 --> 00:25:20.670
what do you think the greatest mistake has
b-, by your own company, by another thing

00:25:20.670 --> 00:25:36.710
that has been a, the greatest mistake made
in this area so far? Chris, you start.

00:25:36.710 --> 00:25:51.130
&gt;&gt;Chris: You know, I'm, I'm new at Google
so I don't have like, a whole long legacy,

00:25:51.130 --> 00:26:04.000
but I think one of the things that was very
interesting to,

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.570
to watch unfold was the interesting, the collapsing
of context with Buzz and Gmail. So, we use

00:26:09.570 --> 00:26:17.200
Buzz internally at Google, to great effect
I think. And it's been a very, very positive

00:26:17.200 --> 00:26:22.680
thing, especially when I first started working
at Google, it was a great way to learn about

00:26:22.680 --> 00:26:24.381
my coworkers and learn what was going on.

00:26:24.381 --> 00:26:25.381
[clears throat]

00:26:25.381 --> 00:26:28.680
One of the things that's very interesting
about dogfooding a lot of these things is

00:26:28.680 --> 00:26:38.370
that we learn about the products early. We
try them out. We get great use cases. And

00:26:38.370 --> 00:26:47.590
we have a very clear, I think, idea about
how email works and how Buzz works and things

00:26:47.590 --> 00:26:51.970
like that and so, watching peoples, I guess,
questions about--

00:26:51.970 --> 00:26:55.530
&gt;&gt;Kara: I would say horror, but go ahead.

00:26:55.530 --> 00:27:04.870
&gt;&gt;Chris: Questions about the way that they
interpreted Buzz being in their inbox was

00:27:04.870 --> 00:27:15.930
something that was fascinating, I guess. Because
it's like, oh, like people expect that if

00:27:15.930 --> 00:27:24.010
there's this public context within an inbox
then all of a sudden their inbox is gonna

00:27:24.010 --> 00:27:31.920
be made public as well. And, of course, that's
not the case and never was the case, but there

00:27:31.920 --> 00:27:38.070
were a lot of people that had that concern.
And I think that there's also a greater context

00:27:38.070 --> 00:27:42.220
where there's been conversations happening
about Facebook and about Twitter and about

00:27:42.220 --> 00:27:43.600
all these other social services where people
just hadn't anticipated this type of social

00:27:43.600 --> 00:27:47.042
environment to be merged in this very different
type of social environment.

00:27:47.042 --> 00:27:50.460
&gt;&gt;Kara: Well, it's the way you got in, the
way you're trying to get in. Facebook has

00:27:50.460 --> 00:27:56.130
sort of run away with the other part. Right?

00:27:56.130 --> 00:28:04.350
&gt;&gt;Chris: You said it. So, I think it's been
interesting to see that unfold and I, I, one

00:28:04.350 --> 00:28:10.710
of the things that I'm most excited about
with the APIs is to actually allow people

00:28:10.710 --> 00:28:15.140
to build external and different context for
the, the Buzz experience--

00:28:15.140 --> 00:28:16.140
&gt;&gt;Kara: Ok.

00:28:16.140 --> 00:28:21.900
&gt;&gt;Chris: that can give people a different
type of social expectation or social environment

00:28:21.900 --> 00:28:25.600
in which to conduct their daily activity.

00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:33.030
&gt;&gt;Kara: Do you think it was a question of
communication, or that Google people just

00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:36.630
aren't like other people, regular people?

00:28:36.630 --> 00:28:37.630
[laughter]

00:28:37.630 --> 00:28:38.630
&gt;&gt;Chris: I think--

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:50.970
&gt;&gt;Kara: I'm saying the last one is true no
matter how you slice it, but what do you think

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:52.490
the problem was?

00:28:52.490 --> 00:29:07.970
&gt;&gt;Chris: There's something special about Googlers,
for sure. But I think, I think there's also

00:29:07.970 --> 00:29:19.520
a different type of expectation and desire
that a lot of us have at Google to be able

00:29:19.520 --> 00:29:23.050
to share one another.

00:29:23.050 --> 00:29:35.120
&gt;&gt;Kara: Your test group of dogfood eating
was not a usual group of people.

00:29:35.120 --> 00:29:46.110
&gt;&gt;Chris: It was, for someone new to Google,
it was very eye opening.

00:29:46.110 --> 00:29:49.420
&gt;&gt;Kara: Mm-hmm, ok.

00:29:49.420 --> 00:29:54.470
&gt;&gt;Neil: You know, I think one of the interesting
things about Yahoo is that, you know, collapsing

00:29:54.470 --> 00:29:58.960
context is, is not just an exception like
Buzz and, and Gmail kind of combination. It's

00:29:58.960 --> 00:30:04.230
more like, you know, taking ev--, a scoop
of everything at Baskin-Robbins and, and putting

00:30:04.230 --> 00:30:10.400
it in a blender and then mixing in some motor
oil and then saying, "Mmm, drink this."

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:11.400
[Kara laughs]

00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:12.720
You know, yeah, they did. It is, it's a new
product. The McSlurry.

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:13.860
[audience laughs]

00:30:13.860 --> 00:30:21.280
But, you know, the interesting thing is, you
know, we had these; we had listings properties,

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:30.250
right? Where, where folks where they're at
Hotjobs. You know, you were there for sort

00:30:30.250 --> 00:30:39.300
of this commercial intent job seeking. We
had Yahoo Personals where you were there looking

00:30:39.300 --> 00:30:44.610
for somebody but you sure as hell didn't want
anyone to know you were looking for somebody.

00:30:44.610 --> 00:30:52.270
And then we have email. And then have photos
in the form of Flickr. And then we have media

00:30:52.270 --> 00:30:57.370
experiences where sometimes it's programmed
and other times it's sharing, it's groups,

00:30:57.370 --> 00:31:05.100
it's answers, it's message boards, it's all
these sorts of things. And so the biggest

00:31:05.100 --> 00:31:13.720
challenge, and I think, the thing that we
never really have solved and, and has again,

00:31:13.720 --> 00:31:24.630
led to some of our conservativism is it's
seemingly impossible to cross all of those

00:31:24.630 --> 00:31:42.200
streams. Is that if you start with a sort
of vertical notion, you know, whether it's,

00:31:42.200 --> 00:31:52.230
it's sort of LinkedIn, right? It's, its business
oriented, it's very specific, the purpose

00:31:52.230 --> 00:31:59.480
is there. Or even Twitter where it's a channel.
You just say, "Look, I've got a channel and

00:31:59.480 --> 00:32:03.700
I'll let the user program it in any way they
want." It's, it's fairly straightforward to

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:11.651
go ahead and manage that. And so I think one
of the reasons we've been slower and, and

00:32:11.651 --> 00:32:15.850
have missed other opportunities, if you will,
that other folks have captured, like 360,

00:32:15.850 --> 00:32:21.750
is that it, there's no compatible way to mix
all of the Yahoo pieces together. And so I

00:32:21.750 --> 00:32:24.950
think that remains a challenge.

00:32:24.950 --> 00:32:28.740
&gt;&gt;Kara: It wasn't confusing to the user.

00:32:28.740 --> 00:32:32.490
&gt;&gt;Neil: Right. It wasn't confusing and therefore,
we didn't do it, right?

00:32:32.490 --> 00:32:40.180
&gt;&gt;Kara: Cause it does freak them out. I remember
when Facebook went on The Huffington Post

00:32:40.180 --> 00:32:49.490
and think, and I didn't turn the thing off
and I wasn't in stealth mode and then I realized,

00:32:49.490 --> 00:32:54.680
everyone realizes, all I read is Brittney
Spears' stories and Lindsey Lohan's stories,

00:32:54.680 --> 00:32:55.680
so.

00:32:55.680 --> 00:32:56.680
&gt;&gt;Neil: We knew.

00:32:56.680 --> 00:32:57.680
[laughter]

00:32:57.680 --> 00:33:01.620
&gt;&gt;Kara: I know you knew, but, arrested! She's
getting, she is, by the way.

00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:02.620
[laughter]

00:33:02.620 --> 00:33:06.840
When she enters the state again, she'll be
in jail, deservedly. So, but I mean, I think

00:33:06.840 --> 00:33:12.010
it was the lack of; it doesn't mix. I was
just reading The Huffington Post and all of

00:33:12.010 --> 00:33:16.070
a sudden I was sharing my strange predilections
on celebrities and--

00:33:16.070 --> 00:33:26.710
&gt;&gt;Neil: Right. And you know, we, we had an
internal discussion recently about Facebook-like

00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:40.330
buttons. You know, the thing is when you share
something on Yahoo, i--, it's not as bad as

00:33:40.330 --> 00:33:52.190
here you're stalker buddy is gonna see it,
but we, you know, we are sort of in your face.

00:33:52.190 --> 00:34:15.539
It's a proactive notification and there's
a message that says, "This is who it's gonna

00:34:15.539 --> 00:34:34.079
go to." If we were to take, you know, like
buttons and put them all over our media pages

00:34:34.079 --> 00:34:49.139
or sports or you wanted to like a team or
like a sports figure, there's no notification.

00:34:49.139 --> 00:35:01.049
It's a different model and so, so maybe it's
ok for those users for a while until you know,

00:35:01.049 --> 00:35:02.940
again, the next, the next--

00:35:02.940 --> 00:35:04.230
&gt;&gt;Kara: They realize.

00:35:04.230 --> 00:35:14.240
&gt;&gt;Neil: the next boo-boo or mistake happens,
but you know, we found that even the open

00:35:14.240 --> 00:35:24.380
parts of the Web are a bit more promiscuous
than our users are willing to take.

00:35:24.380 --> 00:35:29.400
&gt;&gt;Kara: What about at MySpace or anywhere
else?

00:35:29.400 --> 00:35:34.000
&gt;&gt;Chris Cole: So, I would say--

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:36.299
[audience member coughs]

00:35:36.299 --> 00:35:46.801
with regards to privacy, there's probably
two mistakes I've seen over the years. The

00:35:46.801 --> 00:36:01.529
first one would be to initially over allow
photos and things that should be private to

00:36:01.529 --> 00:36:10.290
get out there. Like, early on you alluded
to a lot of the problems with the under 18

00:36:10.290 --> 00:36:15.339
versus over 18 and then how do you manage
privacy between these groups. And because

00:36:15.339 --> 00:36:25.520
of those early mistakes, the company overcorrected
and has been very conservative in how we allow

00:36:25.520 --> 00:36:28.470
people to share. And in some ways, I think
we put in undue friction, like when we initially

00:36:28.470 --> 00:36:32.750
launched the Developer Platform one was allowed
to invite one friend at a time to share some

00:36:32.750 --> 00:36:39.500
sort of game or app with them. And the reaction
was developers found workarounds to that that

00:36:39.500 --> 00:36:45.640
were incredibly annoying to the user and we've
missed on opportunities like Twitters broadcast

00:36:45.640 --> 00:36:48.960
channel that perhaps we would've been really
well positioned to have taken advantage of

00:36:48.960 --> 00:36:50.910
had we continually re-examined this notion
of privacy. So, it's, it's a really hard line

00:36:50.910 --> 00:36:57.829
to walk where you're private enough that you're
not damaging your user base but public enough

00:36:57.829 --> 00:37:01.279
that you're allowing people to have social
experiences.

00:37:01.279 --> 00:37:08.980
&gt;&gt;Adam: Yeah, you know when I think of different
challenges we've had here, actually we similar

00:37:08.980 --> 00:37:18.470
to Yahoo may have had a little bit of the
reverse where. I'm very excited that we were

00:37:18.470 --> 00:37:24.859
able to launch the open developer platform
with LinkedIn around Thanksgiving; that was

00:37:24.859 --> 00:37:33.119
only about six months ago. Until then, you
know, people who wanted to build business

00:37:33.119 --> 00:37:42.161
applications or other applications to integrate
with LinkedIn, they either had to queue up

00:37:42.161 --> 00:37:53.690
and wait for personal attention, which, of
course, being a small company was hard to

00:37:53.690 --> 00:38:04.600
provide. Or they'd have to find another way
through the shadows, through the grey areas.

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:14.950
And you know, everyone knows, we're all very
clever. We can come up with clever ways to

00:38:14.950 --> 00:38:24.240
solve these problems. You know, one of the
benefits of having an open platform now means

00:38:24.240 --> 00:38:36.640
that first of all, our users have come to
expect that they've invested a lot of time

00:38:36.640 --> 00:38:42.440
in their LinkedIn identities; they don't really
understand why all applications don't have

00:38:42.440 --> 00:38:49.619
access to that information. They expect that
if they give permission they should be able

00:38:49.619 --> 00:38:57.279
to access that anywhere on the Web. But more
importantly, it brings that activity in to

00:38:57.279 --> 00:39:12.180
the light. Right now, people are using a real,
robust authentication system. People are now

00:39:12.180 --> 00:39:28.880
putting all that activity through in a way
that our standards for privacy can be enforced

00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:47.029
across all those interactions. So, while I'm
very proud that we have that open platform

00:39:47.029 --> 00:40:15.390
today and we're actively working on improving
it and expanding it, I think it was a mistake

00:40:15.390 --> 00:40:35.289
to not have it until six months ago. I mean,
there were a lot of things we were figuring

00:40:35.289 --> 00:40:49.660
out, but I'm glad that we have it now.

00:40:49.660 --> 00:41:11.770
&gt;&gt;Angus: A few people have talked about missed
opportunities and I think that what I would

00:41:11.770 --> 00:41:31.619
like to see more of is actually spending time
together working on these complex problems.

00:41:31.619 --> 00:41:50.700
So, like, I was just at an Internet Identity
